(# Nearest-Neighbor Summary \(RTX 5090\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Measured totals only. All numbers below were collected on the user-provided RTX 5090 VM.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Cell format: `query_ms / recall@10`.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Benchmark matrix:) Tj
T*
(- Distribution sweep: `distribution in {gaussian, uniform, laplace}`, `d in {8,16,32,64}`, ) Tj
T*
(`m=250,000`, `n=1000`) Tj
T*
(- Gaussian query scaling: `d in {8,16,32,64}`, `m=250,000`, `n in {100,1000,3000}`) Tj
T*
(- Gaussian database scaling: `d in {8,16,32,64}`, `n=1000`, `m in {100,000,250,000,500,000}`) Tj
T*
(- `k=10` throughout) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Distribution definitions:) Tj
T*
(- `gaussian`: each coordinate is i.i.d. `N\(0, 1\)`) Tj
T*
(- `uniform`: each coordinate is i.i.d. `U\(-sqrt\(3\), sqrt\(3\)\)`, so variance is `1`) Tj
T*
(- `laplace`: each coordinate is i.i.d. `Laplace\(0, 1/sqrt\(2\)\)`, so variance is `1`) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Main takeaways:) Tj
T*
(- `BF-INT8` is the fastest brute-force variant in every Gaussian `n`- and `m`-scaling case, ) Tj
T*
(with recall typically `0.93-0.96`.) Tj
T*
(- `BF-FP16` is the best high-recall brute-force path on this 5090 sweep; it stays near ) Tj
T*
(`0.999+` recall and is consistently faster than `BF-FP32`.) Tj
T*
(- `BF-GEMM` remains much slower than the custom brute-force kernels at these problem sizes, ) Tj
T*
(which is consistent with the CuPy tile-materialization and top-k overhead discussed ) Tj
T*
(elsewhere in the repo.) Tj
T*
(- `IVF-INT8\(C=128,p=8\)` is the fastest approximate method in the cross-distribution sweep, ) Tj
T*
(but its recall drops sharply as `d` increases.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
